pening the ground as a zone that can precede, penetrate, or fracture the figure. David Young Kim looks at the work of Gentile da Fabriano, Giovanni Bellini, Giovanni Battista Moroni, and Caravaggio, reconstructing each painter’s methods to demonstrate the intricacies involved in laying ground layers whose translucency and polychromy permeate the surface. He charts significant transitions from gold ground painting in the Trecento to the darkened grounds in Baroque tenebrism, and offers close readings of period texts to shed new light on the significance of ground forms such as rock face, wall, and cave.This beautifully illustrated book reconceives the Renaissance picture, revealing the passion and mystery of groundwork and discovering figuration beyond the human figure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aBackground (Art) 0aGround (Coatings) 0aPainting, Italian. 0aPainting, RenaissancezItaly. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAdage.  aAltarpiece.  aArma Christi.  aArt history.  aBasilica.  aBembo.  aBlack people.  aCalligraphy.  aCaravaggio.  aCennino Cennini.  aChiaroscuro.  aDaniele da Volterra.  aDe architectura.  aDepiction.  aDomenico Fetti.  aDosso Dossi.  aDuccio.  aEssay.  aFabulation.  aFall of Simon Magus (Pompeo Batoni).  aFigurative art.  aFigure of speech.  aFilarete.  aFra Angelico.  aFrick Collection.  aFriedrich Nietzsche.  aGalleria Borghese.  aGalleria Nazionale dell'Umbria.  aGentile da Fabriano.  aGesso.  aGilding.  aGiorgio Vasari.  aGiotto.  aGiovanni Baglione.  aGiovanni Battista Moroni.  aGiovanni Bellini.  aGiovanni Boccaccio.  aGiulio Romano.  aGiuseppe Cesari.  aGold leaf.  aGrisaille.  aHenry Clay Frick.  aIconography.  aImpasto.  aImprimatura.  aItalian Renaissance.  aJacopo Bassano.  